# Rust standards

- Prefer `Result<T, E>` over panics. `unwrap`/`expect` are for tests
  and truly-unreachable invariants only, never for handling real input
  or IO.
- Borrow before you clone. A `.clone()` needs a reason (crossing an
  ownership boundary, needed for a later mutation) — don't reach for it
  by default to make the borrow checker quiet.
- Arena allocation (`slotmap` / `generational-arena`) for AST and graph
  nodes, not `Box<Node>` trees — see `docs/01-grid-engine-core-spec.md`.
  This avoids per-node heap churn on the hot paths (parsing, formula
  evaluation, dependency recalculation).
- Public items (`pub fn`, `pub struct`, `pub enum`, `pub trait`) get a
  `///` doc comment explaining what they do, not just their signature
  restated in prose.
- `cargo fmt --check` and `cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets -- -D
  warnings` must both be clean before a change is done — this is what
  CI enforces, don't leave it to CI to catch first.

## Unit tests

Every module ships its tests inline via `#[cfg(test)] mod tests`,
colocated in the same file as the code it tests. Every public function
gets at minimum one test for its primary behavior and one for an edge
case — empty input, a boundary value, or an error path, whichever is
relevant.

For functions with many input variations (formula parsing, cell ID
packing, dependency graph traversal), prefer a table-driven test: one
`#[test]` function iterating over a slice of `(input, expected)` cases,
rather than a wall of near-identical individual test functions.

See `crates/gridyard-core/src/lib.rs`'s `cell_id` function and its
tests for the pattern this repo follows.
